<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Leymus</i> <i>condensatus</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Avena</i> <i>fatua</i>, <i>Brassica</i> <i>nigra</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>diandrus</i>, <i>Centaurea</i> <i>melitensis</i>, <i>Hirschfeldia</i> <i>incana</i> and <i>Malacothrix</i> <i>saxatilis</i>. Emergent trees and shrubs may be present at low cover, including trees <i>Juglans</i> <i>californica</i> or <i>Quercus</i> <i>agrifolia</i> and shrubs:<i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>salicifolia</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>leucophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 3 m; cover is open to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Leymus condensatus</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006, Verdone and Evens 2010, Sproul et al. 2011, Buck-Diaz et al. 2015).</li>
		
		<li><i>Leymus condensatus</i> > 30% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Rodriguez et al. 2017).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Somewhat steep, often northerly slopes at low elevations. Soils are loams. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Leymus condensatus</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
