    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Leymus condensatus</i> includes Central California Coast (261A), Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), Mojave Desert (322A), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-j). Stands occur at the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2005) and occupy dry hill slopes adjacent to the Santa Clara River (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007). They are large patches surrounded by annual grasslands or recovering stands of <i>Salvia leucophylla</i> and other coastal scrub alliances. Stands have been recorded on the Channel Islands where they were found in moist swales, including Anacapa, San Miguel, and Santa Catalina (Rodriguez et al. 2017, Dixon et al. 2019). Stands have been recorded on the Palos Verdes Peninsula (Verdone and Evens 2010), in Orange County (Buck-Diaz and Evens 2015), on Camp Pendleton and elsewhere in western San Diego County (Sproul et al. 2011)</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Keeley (2002b) suggested that Native Americans used <i>Leymus condensatus </i>and maintained stands by burning. Plants increase after fires, but individuals persist independently of fire in areas of human disturbance and in areas where slumping and seepage occur (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). </div>
</div>

    

    

